Thank you also @0xlosha for helping us recover all the funds today and giving his feedback on the contract!
9) It was incredibly stressful but I'm really glad I was able to resolve this for everyone and am thrilled to see so much activity today. Thank you for your patience.

8) Since this was the third contract I deployed using on the testnet, I had to deploy three contracts on the mainnet as well until it hit this address.

The contract only contained a basic withdraw function that withdrew the ETH to my wallet. Funds were secured.
7) More importantly, it means if I also deployed contracts on the mainnet, one of those contracts would end up on this address, letting me control its funds.

6) Next, how did we get the funds out from that address? 

0x36eceabaa19e023586a1c28e45e8dd98e8352b82 is a contract on the Rinkeby testnet. That means I had deployed to it with an address I owned.
5) In the end, we just forcefully cleared out the cache ourselves and kicked off a new build, and the site was fixed, with no changes to the code.

5) Yup - this old address, DESPITE me setting the correct address.

The production server wasn't exactly 1:1 with my test server. Since I had tested with it the night before, it ended up caching (saving) this config file and did not update it, even when I changed its contents.

4) The night before, this config had a different address on the Rinkeby testnet: 

https://t.co/LiIdfyJq79

Guess which address ended up being used today?

3) On our server, we store a configuration file that holds the smart contract address (see below)

Prior to our presale, I set the correct address on this config. I know this because, as stated above, I had this working on another server and was able to mint presale just fine. https://t.co/npMI1FJ3E2

2) At the time of the presale - I had a copy of the presale site working perfectly on a different domain. You would imagine - if I run this exact same code with the exact same configuration on a the exact server setup, you would get the same result. Unfortunately, that's not true

1) Preface:

It had nothing to do with poor coding, not checking the contract addresses, or a bad contract. It had everything to do with the deployment of the website and how build caches work.

I would not have deployed the production server without testing.
